class Solution {
    public String largestMerge(String word1, String word2) {
        StringBuilder merge = new StringBuilder();
        while (!word1.isEmpty() || !word2.isEmpty()) {
            if (!word1.isEmpty() && !word2.isEmpty()) {
                if (word1.compareTo(word2) > 0) {
                    merge.append(word1.charAt(0));
                    word1 = word1.substring(1);
                } else {
                    merge.append(word2.charAt(0));
                    word2 = word2.substring(1);
                }
            } else if (!word1.isEmpty()) {
                merge.append(word1);
                word1 = "";
            } else {
                merge.append(word2);
                word2 = "";
            }
        }
        return merge.toString();
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n*m)
space complexity: O(n+m)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution compares the remaining parts of the input strings at each step and appends the larger one to the result, ensuring the lexicographically largest merge. It handles remaining characters in either string once one is exhausted.
